title: The conversion from 3-byte to an int is wrong
body:
- The right way is `return (bytes[offset] & 0xFF) << 16 | (bytes[offset + 1] & 0xFF) << 8 | (bytes[offset + 2] & 0xFF);`

- The unit test must be completed to cover the case where bytes at offset 1 or 2 are > 127

title: Remotese : study how to replace dtoNode by a publishing queue
body:
At the moment a DtoNode is responsible to 'send' and receive keypleDto. 

In a custom architecture, the dtoNode does not send the keypleDto, instead they are sent and received by 3rd party components.
Those components will not implement the dtoNode interface, then the DtoNode interface does not make sense.

Proposal : 
MasterAPI and SlaveAPI publish the dto to queues.
The 3rd party component should listen to the queues and send the keypleDto to the right node. When the response is received, the 3rd party component should publish it to the queues.

NB : the current architecture allows this proposal by creating DtoNode that manages queues.

This requires early analysis of FCI data (as part of the selection process).

title: Added a mechanism to avoid unwanted repeated selections
body:
After a properly completed transaction, the SE can be detected and selected again as it is removed from the electromagnetic field.

To avoid this, we must introduce a parameter specifying a time period during which the same SE will be ignored in the selection step.

This feature is to be implemented in AbstractLocalReader, giving this capability to all local readers.

title: keyple-core : unecessary exception in getReaders()
body: Study if we need the KeypleReaderException in plugin#getReaders()

title: NA
body: This exception is needed to notify the fact that the readers list is null, generally resulting in an error of initialization of the readers list at the instantiation of the plugin.

title: NA
body:
At the end of the registering of a plugin on SeProxyService, we could maybe check if the reader list is ‚Äúnull‚Äù.

- If it‚Äôs the case, we could consider that the registering of the plugin has failed, and then issues an Exception.
 
When registered a ReaderPlugin could have a list of SeReader: empty or with some items. But never null.

- So `ReaderPlugin .getReaders()` doesn‚Äôt necessary need an exception.

- But `SeProxyService registerPlugin(AbstractPluginFactory pluginFactory)` as it is currently defined, has to throw an exception.

title: NA
body:
Using null value is discouraged, so it will be better to stick with exceptions. 

The proposed solution uses a KeypleRuntimeException in the constructor of the plugin that can be caught by the factory if a problem arose when instantiating the plugin.

The factory is now notified of the problem and can throw an exception too.

Then we don't .getReaders() to throw an exception to notify a problem of initialization.

title: Manage inconsistencies between the SAM's capabilities and the revision of the presented PO
body:
This problem is related to the case where an SAM that is not able to manage PO Rev3.2 is used and a PO Rev 3.2 is presented.
Old SAMs do not support 8-byte cryptograms (Digest Close command).

title: keyple-core : AbstractThreadedObservablePlugin  clearObservers does not call stopObservation
body: - stopObservation is not called by clearObservers() whereas removeObserver() does call stopObservation when the list is empty

title: keyple-core : AbstractLoggedObservable misleads use
body:
To avoid confusion either remove this class 
or make its method protected :  addObserver() removeObserver()

title: NA
body: #101 : will protect this class

title: NA
body:
Hi,
Could you more specific about what do you try to achieve? Are you building
our NFC example or making your own?

About your error, it seems that gradle is importing the keyple-calypso
classes twice, resulting in the error you shared with us.

Although your gradle seems clean, I'm wondering if you have imported the
mentionned jar in the libs folder or anywhere else than what is described
in the gradle file?

Let us know,

Cheers,
Olivier

title: keyple-plugin-stub: wrong design for StubPluginFactory & StubPluginImpl
body:
Currently StubPluginImpl isn't a singleton: several instances of the plugin could potentially be created.
StubPoolPluginImpl shouldn't contains a StubPluginImpl as attributes. The only link between StubPoolPluginImpl & StubPluginImpl is that both manage SeReader based on StubReaderImpl.

title: NA
body:
Actually, the SeProxyService is responsible for not creating multiple instances of StubPluginImpl. 
StubPoolPluginImpl wraps a StubPluginImpl because it enhances its features with "pool" methods (alternative to extension with more flexilibity)
So I don't think the design is wrong, or am I missing something?

title: NA
body:
I think the problem is elsewhere. If we have an application that uses the StubPlugin for PO and the StubPoolPlugin for SAM, then there will be two usages of the StubPlugin in two different locations in the system: in the main application and in the StubPoolPlugin.
In addition to adding confusion, this mechanism goes against the principle of StubPoolPlugin, whose purpose is to be able to provide an arbitrary (potentially large) number of identical readers.
The solution probably involves a new design of the StubPoolPlugin API. We would no longer pass a StubPluginImpl as a constructor parameter but a list of groupReferences and their associated SE.
During allocation, the StubPoolPlugin creates a StubReader on the fly in which an SE is inserted.
The idea being to reproduce as closely as possible the functioning of an HSM, it seems preferable to carry out the allocation of readers in this way.
In the new API, the plugStubPoolReader and unplugStubPoolReader methods are removed.
I will try to propose an evolution of the API soon.

title: omapi : no error management in plugin register
body:
Error management is not possible at the register level when a plugin calls an asynchronous service to get the initially connected readers. 

In the Omapi plugin, if the platform is not compatible, the application does not receive any error. The plugin initializes but the list of readers is empty.

_Underlying issue : maybe a async register function with error management in the SeProxy can be a solution._

How to register a plugin when the initialization of an external async service is required : 
- 1 : init async service outside of plugin, in this case the error management is handled before calling the register method
- 2 : init async service in factory with a blocking method, this could be a solution for Omapi plugin and others.
- 3 : init async service in plugin, this is the current Omapi plugin, no error management is possible.

Then try to refactor the Omapi to comply with an async way of registering plugin with error management : propose implementation (2) for OMAPI plugin

title: Correct the SamResourceManager in the PC/SC case
body: The SAM reader observation mechanism is not compatible for use in this class.

title: NA
body:
The SamResourceManager PC/SC asks questions that we may not have answered yet!

To put the ideas in place, I give the context back:

- it is a question of dynamically allocating SAM resources to an application (in the form of cards inserted in a PC/SC reader)

- so it is necessary to:
   - monitor reader insertions/removals¬†
   - monitor card insertions/removals in readers
   - manage the case where the card is already present in the reader when the reader is inserted
- the application may also have to manage PO PC/SC readers.

The tricky points are:
- The double monitoring of the PC/SC plugin
   - we can have two observers with in each one a specifc filter (regex) on the names of the readers so that each one "tracks" the readers that are relevant to it (e.g. "Identive.\*" for SAM and"(ASK|ACR).\*" for PO)
   - but the assignment of observers (of Reader) with addObserver leads to annoying behaviors: the addition of the 1st observer (e. g. SAM) starts the observation thread which makes the inventory of the readers present and notifies the only observer present.
     When adding a 2nd observer (PO), the observation thread does nothing more and therefore the new observer is not notified of the presence of the readers (and potentially of the reader that concerns it).
   - the notification of the readers present at startup therefore works well but only for the first observer!
- The case of the card already inserted in the reader when plugged in
   - in the SamResourceManager, we want to add an SE observer to any new reader inserted but at the moment, the notification of the presence of an already inserted SE is not performed.
     When adding the SE observer, we could call isSePresent() to manage this case, but there is a risk of concurrency and double allocation if the same thing is done at the same time by the observer (insertion just after the reader is connected)

It is therefore necessary to define a method and/or mechanisms to address these points.
Any contribution to solving this issue is welcome.

title: NA
body:
"It is a question of dynamically allocating SAM resources to an application (in the form of cards inserted in a PC/SC reader):"

Then the SamResourceManager has two main responsibilities : 
(1) - manage the available resources
(2) - allocate one resource when requested if one is available. 

To answer responsibilities (1), as you stated we can rely on the observation mechanism. But not only, we can also use in combination the explicit methods to get the status of the readers and SE :  getReaders and isSePresent(). The management of available resources can be real-time, or it can be updated when one request is made on (2)

Answering (2) should be precisely specified : 
- if one resource is available, allocate it. it should somehow be marked as busy. Is there a timeout to release it, if the requester doesn't do it?
- if no resource is available because there are none connected, what should we return? 
- if no resource is available because they are busy, should be wait? how long time?

title: NA
body:
After reviewing, the case of the card already inserted in the reader is not a problem. It was an implementation error that put me on the wrong path...

Concerning the SamResourceManager itself and the dynamic allocation of resources, the best answer is probably to create a ReaderPoolPlugin object based on a subset of the available PC/SC readers.

This would have the advantage of simplifying the SamResourceManager class, which currently takes into account both plugin models.

However, it remains the question of how to create independent subsets from a single plugin (PC/SC).

The idea is to rely on the existing plugin and create a kind of wrapper that redirects commands and notifications according to rules based on reader names.

title: NA
body:
Response already commented in https://github.com/eclipse/keyple-java/issues/165

- VirtualReader should implement SeReader, not ObservableReader.

- VirtualObservable should implement ObservableReader.

- If a NativeReader is ObservableReader, then connected with a Remote SE => a VirtualObservableReader should be created.

- If a NativeReader isn't ObservableReader, then connected with a Remote SE => a VirtualReader should be created.

title: For ObservablePlugin, set a PluginObserver to be notified of reader changes, only for readers with names matching a regex
body:
In org.eclipse.keyple.core.seproxy.event.ObservablePlugin the current method

- `void addObserver(PluginObserver observer);`

allows to set an Observer for all the readers of a plugin.

In addition, the definition of a new method 

- `void addObserver(PluginObserver observer, String readerNameRegex);`

will allow an Observer to **be notified for changes on readers only having a name matching a specific regular expression**.

For example, useful for some Calypso use cases, in order to defined from the same plugin an observer of SAM readers, and separately an observer of PO readers.

Linked with the issue eclipse/keyple-service-java-lib#47

title: For AbstractThreadedObservablePlugin, fix the setting of multiple observers on a same ReaderPlugin
body:
When several PluginObserver(s) are defined for a specific ReaderPlugin, the method `notifyObservers` allows to notify sequentially **ALL** the different observers with the same PluginEvent.

As implemented in org.eclipse.keyple.core.seproxy.plugin.AbstractThreadedObservablePlugin, the observation thread of a specific plugin starts when a first PluginObserver is set using the method:

- `public final void addObserver(ObservablePlugin.PluginObserver observer)`

When a terminal processing, implements ReaderObserver, and observes a specific ReaderPlugin, we recommend to not use the GetReaders() method, and to define a processing based on the management of PluginEvent.

So when a PluginObserver is added to a specific ObservablePlugin, the PluginObserver must be notified about the current reader available: notification of a **SINGLE** PluginObserver, the one being added.

In the current implementation of AbstractThreadedObservablePlugin, **only the first** PluginObserver added is notified. A second PluginObserver is not notified of the initial state during its addition to an ObservablePlugin. **This is the issue to fix!**

To avoid side effect during the processing of addObserver:

- I propose at the **beginning** of addObserver processing, to **stop the listening** of the ObservablePlugin. So during the addition of a PluginObserver, the ObservablePlugin will not more notify any PluginEvent.

- Then during the addition of the PluginObserver, the new observer is notified of the current status.

- Finally, the addObserver processing **ends by restarting the listening** of the ObservablePlugin.

title: Remotese : clearObserver method can remove SlaveAPI observer
body:
The method clearObserver has a bad side effect on SlaveAPI.

Use case :  
A local reader is observable, slaveAPI is added as an observer of the local reader when the local reader gets connected. 
If the application invokes clearObservers, it will remove the slaveAPI and then stops the remote se observation mechanism.

Ideas of a solution : 
To avoid this side effect, we might remove the clearObserver method from the ObservableReader interface to avoid application to use it. Instead, the application should use the removeObserver(). 
It implies that the application keep a reference to each Observer it added to the reader, which is acceptable.

title: Add mirroring of card data for Calypso PO
body:
In order to solve future new features (such as #232), it would be helpful to have an image of the information retrieved from the PO during a transaction.
The main idea is to populate a local database (ideally as an extension of CalypsoPo) throughout the execution of a PoTransaction.
CalypsoPo will have new protected setters (accessible from PoTransaction) and public getters (accessible from the application).
The data concerned are the files and all non-volatile statuses of the PO (such as the PIN presentation counter).
The current API (parser index in return for prepare commands) could be conserved to maintain backward compatibility with existing application implementations (at least for some time).

title: NA
body:
The Calypso Keyple extension provides a **high level API** to select a Calypso, to prepare & process PO commands (defined in the package org.eclipse.keyple.calypso.**transaction**)
The way de configure the PO selection and the PO commands is an achievement, involving simple functional commands with simple functional parameters, far from the complexity of the configuration of the PO APDU commands.

- We recover the status and the startup information of the selected PO through the CalypsoPo object.
- A PoTransaction object allows to manage the functionals commands to operate with the CalypsoPo.

But the current PoTransaction presents a strong **weakness**: the current way to recover is based on a ‚Äú**low level** API‚Äù from APDU response parser (defined in the package org.eclipse.keyple.calypso.**command.po.parser**): and the way based ‚Äúcommand index‚Äù to identify what APDU response parser is related to a specific prepared PO command is complex to use. The command index has been defined in order to provide at the command preparation state links to recover PO responses that will be initialize only during the processing of the prepared PO commands.

The purpose of this evolution is to fully hide the complexity of the low level APDU parser API, and to avoid need to parse specific command responses.
The solution is to fill the CalypsoPo & PoTransaction objects with the data parsed in the PO responses:

- To add getters to CalypsoPo to recover **PO data & status**:
  - the data of the PO file structure: file data read or write during the PoTransaction.
  - Stored Value data: amount (current value / unknown), last reload information, last debit information‚Ä¶
  - PO status: like the invalidation status, the PIN status (number of attempts remaining), ‚Ä¶
- To add getters to PoTransaction to recover **transaction states**:
  - PIN verifications state (successful/failed/unknown),
  - secure sessions state (open, closed after a successful authentication, closed after a failed authentication, closed after a cancelled authentication, unknown),
  - stored value transaction state (reload authentication processed/failed, same for debit)


For the ‚ÄòNEXT‚Äô we may be able to extend these CalypsoPo & PoTransaction principles with even higher APIs.
For example, to manage a Hoplink PO: we may be able to define:

- an HoplinkPo object extending CalypsoPo with getters to recover events list, contracts list,
- and an HoplinkTransaction object extending PoTransaction with methods to prepare event/contract search, events/contracts update‚Ä¶

title: calypso : sam manager feedbacks with pcsc plugin
body:
Some feedbacks about using the sam manager with a pcsc and stub reader :
- when no resources are available, it returns null: should it be an exception?
- the sam manager could be a singleton (or declare to the seProxy?), it would be easier to initialize it and use it.
- I would like to check if my setup is successful with a size() method on the created resources.


Some feedbacks about the implementation : 
- SamResourceManager manages pool plugin, observable plugin, and reader plugin in only one implementation whereas the behavior is totally different. It would be good to split it into two implementations. #split 
- If the plugin is observable, the sam manager initialization relies on the observable mechanism. I can imagine cases where it can be a problem. It would be more robust if the initialization would be static and then rely on observability for dynamic changes. #staticinit
- lacks unit testing

title: NA
body:
Yes, when no resource is available, the SAM Manager may return an exception instead of null.

The 'SAM Manager' is a Calypso high level API to obtain "SAM resources".
There could be mainly 3 ways to interface a native SAM to the SAM Manager:

- SAM instances could be provided by a Calypso HSM: in this case the SAM Manager operates a ReaderPoolPlugin.
- SAM instances could also be provided locally through PC/SC readers: in this case the SAM Manager operates a ReaderPlugin.
    - we may allow to allocate only some specific PC/SC readers to the SAM Manager.
    - the flexibility of PC/SC is to allow the hot plug of readers and the acceptance of newly inserted SAM without rebooting the SAM Manager.
 - SAM instances could also be interfaced remotely through the Remote SE plugin.

If the SAM Manager is defined as a singleton, it may allow to be interfaced with a mix different plugin (HSM, PC/SC, Remote SE).

The SAM Manager object couldn‚Äôt be declared to the SE Proxy: the Core API shouldn‚Äôt have dependency with the Calypso API.

The behavior of the HSM and PC/SC plugins are different:
 - for an HSM, as a ReaderPoolPlugin, we can't get the full list of SAM instances, but we can request the allocation of a SAM instance and release: exactly the service proposed by the SAM Manager.
 - for the PC/SC, by observing the PC/SC plugin and the PC/SC reader, the SAM Manager has the possibility to recover a list of PC/SC reader, but SAM Manager not necessary needs to handle all the available PC/SC readers, maybe only a subset. Using https://github.com/eclipse/keyple-service-java-lib/issues/47 the SAM Manager may be able to shortlist only some specific readers, or using https://github.com/eclipse/keyple-java/issues/195 the SAM Manager has the possibility to be notified for events of some specific readers (ATR filter specific for SAM). For PC/SC, the SAM Manager has to manage identified PC/SC readers like ReaderPoolPlugin does (cf. https://github.com/eclipse/keyple-java/issues/148).
The goal of the SAM Manager is to hide the specificities of the SAM suppliers, and to provide SAM resources in a generic way (potentially SAM resources from different suppliers). The SAM Manager may be able to handle several plugins at a time.

title: Access to files in session may fail if specific read commands are executed prior to
body:
Typically, this problem can occur with Calypso PO Rev 2.4 when the RT application is selected and an MPP DF file is read before accessing an in-session RT file. Reading the MPP file causes the MPP DF to implicitly select the MPP DF which causes the following commands to fail. The following sequence shows the issue: 
00 A4 04 00 08 31 54 49 43 2E 49 43 41 00 // select application
94 B2 01 C4 00 // read record SFI=18, rec=1 
94 8A 82 00 04 F8 34 D9 BF 00 // open secure session
94 DC 01 4C 17 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF // update record (SFI=9, rec=1)
The last command (update record / DC) returns 6982 because the read record command (B2) changed the currently selected DF (SFI = 18). The purpose of this issue is to memorize the fact, the short-term technical solution is to document it.

The problem is, when any runtime exception is called on this new thread, before or after the "update" , the thread is killed and no information is logged.
It could be better to make a call back on the readerObserver to inform the user that the exception was called and the thread will be killed, giving him/her the possibility to clean, log or whatever he/she wants.

title: An alive background Thread prevent Main from stopping
body:
Here is a simple main :

https://gist.github.com/alexandre-jannotta/1d4cb6abc82397f0132bb048012f09f6

A background Thread "pool-1-thread-1" generated by Keyple prevent process exit.

Could you please fix this ?

title: NA
body:
Hello Alexandre,

First of all, thank you for contributing to the improvement of Keyple!

Concerning the background thread you're talking about, there are indeed threads created by Keyple notably for monitoring plugins (inserting readers) and readers (presenting secure elements).

The logic of Keyple is to start these threads as needed when observers are added and these threads are stopped when observers are removed.

Moreover, the principle of using Keyple in "observed" (vs. "explicit") mode is to start observing the readers and then to keep the application in an endless wait (a bit like the Calypso/Demo_CalypsoClassic_Pcsc example illustrates briefly).

In your example, the "test" method called by "main" does not implement this waiting and does not remove the observer added at startup.
It is therefore logical that a "ghost" thread persists at exit.

I hope I have answered the question, but if I have not, I remain available to provide further information on the operation and implementation of Keyple.

This being said, we are preparing the release of a new version 0.9 which revisits in depth some aspects of the Keyple API, in particular facilitating the realization of applications.

You can already use a snapshot version (develop branch) or wait a week or two.

body:
Hello zemoa,
The easiest way to use the latest `'develop'` version of Keyple is to specify this in a `gradle.properties` file (to be placed next to `build.gradle`).
For example:
```
keyple_version=0.9.0-SNAPSHOT
```
It is also possible to be more specific about targeting a particular date of SNAPSHOT by changing `keyple_v` in each dependency declaration defined in `build.gradle`.

```
    implementation group: 'org.eclipse.keyple', name: 'keyple-java-core', version: '0.9.0-20200710.143658-40'
    implementation group: 'org.eclipse.keyple', name: 'keyple-java-calypso', version: '0.9.0-20200710.143713-40'
    implementation group: 'org.eclipse.keyple', name: 'keyple-java-plugin-pcsc', version: '0.9.0-20200710.143750-40'
    implementation group: 'org.eclipse.keyple', name: 'keyple-java-plugin-stub', version: '0.9.0-20200710.143839-40'
```
Note that due to timestamp naming, the CI produces SNAPSHOT version numbers that are not quite identical for each module.
The SNAPSHOT repository can be found here:
https://oss.sonatype.org/content/repositories/snapshots/org/eclipse/keyple/
The files to be taken into account are those prefixed by 'keyple-java'.

title: PCSC Reader does not throw exception when disconnect on MacOS
body:
The PCSC reader uses a different implementation on Mac OS than Windows. 

When a pcsc reader gets disconnected, the user does not receive any Exception. On the other hand, if the reader is observable, the user receive a DISCONNECT_READER event **which is the right way to be informed of such an event.**

The root cause of this mecanism is that on MacOS the PCSC implementation uses the method CardTerminal#isCardPresent() that does not throw an exception if the CardTerminal is disconnected, instead it returns false.

title: NA
body:
In the above log, the problem occurs more than 5 seconds after the last communication with the SAM.
This reminds me a problem with Windows that resets the card after 5 seconds of non-use.
Can you try to change the Smartcard Group Policy as described here:
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/security/identity-protection/smart-cards/smart-card-group-policy-and-registry-settings

In practice (the explanations of Microsoft are not clear) :
- open an admin console
- launch gepedit.msc
- disable all points in Computer configuration -> Administrative templates -> Windows components -> Smart card
- restart the PC

title: RATIFICATION
body:
there is a bug in Keyple 1.0.0, concerning the session closing which sends a ratification command to the card even if
the close session command specifies that the ratification is automatic (80H)

The fix is simple : 
-->Change in PoTransaction.java L454: CLOSE_RATIFIED to CLOSE_NOT_RATIFIED

title: NA
body:
Hello,

As indicated on the repository homepage, **Keyple 1.0 is no longer maintained**.

Many corrections and improvements have been made in version 2.0

Here is the link to the project website: https://keyple.org/
